## Role-Based UI

Switch roles using the dropdown at the bottom of the sidebar.

**Admin**
- Can add transactions (button in Transactions header, or Ctrl+N)
- Can edit any transaction (pencil icon per row)
- Can delete any transaction (trash icon, with confirmation)
- Sees all action columns

**Viewer**
- All data is visible; all charts and insights work normally
- A blue notice banner appears at the top of each page
- Add, Edit, and Delete controls are hidden (not just disabled)
- Switching back to Admin immediately restores all controls

Role and theme choices are saved to localStorage and restored on the next visit.

---

## State Management

All application state lives in a single `S` object that acts as a thin localStorage adapter:

```
S.txns   → transaction array (read/write, JSON serialised)
S.theme  → 'dark' | 'light'
S.role   → 'admin' | 'viewer'
S.page   → last visited page name
```

UI state (current page, pagination, sort/filter values) lives in plain JS variables and is derived on each render — no stale cache to manage. Render functions are pure in the sense that they always read from `txns` and the DOM filter inputs, so the UI is always consistent with the data.

The mock API layer (`mockApi` object) wraps all mutations in `async/await` with realistic random delays (280–600ms). This means the save and delete flows are genuinely async — the UI disables the save button and shows "Saving…" while the call is in flight, then shows a toast on resolution. Switching to a real REST API would only require replacing the three methods on `mockApi`.

---

## Mock API

```js
mockApi.fetchTransactions()    // GET  — resolves with full txns array (~600–1000ms)
mockApi.saveTransaction(payload) // POST/PUT — resolves with saved object (~350ms)
mockApi.deleteTransaction(id)    // DELETE — resolves with { success, id } (~280ms)
```

To wire up a real backend, replace these three functions with `fetch()` calls. No other code changes needed — all callers already handle the returned promises.

