## File Structure

Everything is in one file for portability. Internally it's organised into clear sections marked with banner comments:

```
finance-dashboard.html
  ├── <style>
  │     ├── Theme tokens (CSS custom properties, dark + light)
  │     ├── Reset & base
  │     ├── Sidebar
  │     ├── Topbar
  │     ├── Pages & animations
  │     ├── Loading skeleton
  │     ├── Toast system
  │     ├── Summary cards
  │     ├── Chart cards
  │     ├── Buttons & filters
  │     ├── Table & badges
  │     ├── Pagination
  │     ├── Empty states
  │     ├── Modals (add/edit, confirm delete)
  │     ├── Insights
  │     └── Responsive breakpoints (1100px, 768px, 480px)
  ├── <body>
  │     ├── Sidebar (nav + role switcher)
  │     ├── Topbar (title + theme toggle + avatar)
  │     ├── Loading skeleton
  │     ├── Page: Dashboard
  │     ├── Page: Transactions
  │     ├── Page: Insights
  │     ├── Modal: Add / Edit transaction
  │     └── Modal: Confirm delete
  └── <script>
        ├── State (S adapter + txns array)
        ├── Mock API
        ├── Formatting helpers
        ├── Toast system
        ├── Theme
        ├── Role
        ├── Navigation
        ├── Data computed (totals, category rollups)
        ├── Dashboard render
        ├── Charts (Chart.js, with theme-aware colours)
        ├── Transactions (filter, sort, paginate, render)
        ├── CRUD (add, edit, delete with mock API)
        ├── Export (CSV + JSON)
        ├── Insights render
        ├── Mobile sidebar
        ├── Keyboard shortcuts
        └── Init (boot sequence with skeleton loader)
```

---

## Design Decisions

**Single file** — zero setup friction. Anyone with the file can open it immediately without npm, a bundler, or environment variables.

**DM Serif Display + DM Mono + Outfit** — the serif gives the logo and modal titles character; the mono makes financial figures scannable; Outfit keeps body text clean without the genericness of Inter or Roboto.

**Dark-first with full light mode** — every colour is a CSS custom property. Switching themes swaps the token values; no hardcoded hex values appear in component styles. Charts recalculate their colour arguments from the current theme on every rebuild.

**Animated number counters** — summary card values ease in on load and whenever data changes, using `requestAnimationFrame` with a cubic-ease function. This draws attention to changes without being distracting.

**Defensive empty states** — every table and list checks for empty data and renders a centred illustration with a descriptive message and a contextual action button, rather than showing a blank area or broken layout.

**Confirmation before delete** — destructive actions go through a modal confirmation step with the transaction name shown, so users can verify they're deleting the right record.

**Filter chips** — active filters are reflected as removable chips above the table, giving users a clear picture of what's applied and letting them remove individual filters without clearing everything.

---

## Browser Support

Works in any modern browser (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge). No polyfills needed. Uses:
- CSS custom properties (variables)
- CSS Grid and Flexbox
- `async/await`
- `localStorage`
- `requestAnimationFrame`
- Chart.js 4.4.1 (loaded from cdnjs)
- Google Fonts (loaded from fonts.googleapis.com)

Offline use: fonts and Chart.js require an internet connection on first load. After that, browsers cache both aggressively.

---

## Assumptions

- All monetary values are in USD.
- The 25 seed transactions cover January–June 2025 and serve as realistic demo data.
- The 180-day window used for "average daily spend" is fixed to match the seed data period.
- Monthly chart data for the trend and income/expense charts uses static illustrative figures rather than being computed from the seed transactions (which only partially cover each month). This is a reasonable assumption for a frontend-only demo — a real backend would return pre-aggregated monthly summaries.
- "This month" in the Insights page is hardcoded to June 2025 to match the seed data. In production this would use `new Date()`.

